Russian President Vladimir Putin has signed a law on imposing administrative responsibility for violating the term and order of payment of goods (works, services) when purchasing for state and municipal needs.
This law is designed to solve a very acute problem of non-fulfillment of their obligations by customers when carrying out state and municipal purchases.
Two years ago, the situation was widespread when entrepreneurs could not get paid for their public and municipal contracts.
At the same time, the Russian president instructed the Russian General Prosecutor's Office to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unfaithful customers who signed contracts not backed by financing, tried to evade their payment obligations and included illegal terms in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in the interests of protecting the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment by public orders, the prosecutor's office has submitted 9,7 thousand submissions, as a result of their consideration, 4,5 thousand officials have been brought to disciplinary responsibility, and administrative - 533 - 75 documents have been submitted to the investigatory bodies for the organization of procedural checks, 46 of which have been brought to trial.
As a result, the debts of over 66 billion rubles were paid off to the entrepreneurs.
And these huge sums of money were not built up by the failure to pay off multi-billion dollar contracts.
The basic debts were accompanied by numerous, systematic delays in paying services to entrepreneurs at much more modest amounts.
This is a typical case.
The head of a small company won a competition for social transportation services for several million rubles.
The man invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled his obligations, but did not get the money due on time.
The result is a growing financial debt of wages, taxes, loans that would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not turned to the prosecutor's office for help.
Now, in some regions, the problem has been leveled to the maximum.
Nevertheless, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts, as identified by prosecutors of the Russian Federation's subjects, amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt levels continue to reach critical levels, the prosecutor's office operates in a manual crisis management mode.
The Prosecutor General shall personally hold meetings with local authorities, where all violations discovered by the prosecutors are examined and measures taken to remedy them are taken.
Such operational meetings have already been held in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg this year.
The implementation of Federal law No 189-FZ "On amendments to the Code of the Russian Federation on administrative offences in the area of determining administrative responsibility of the officials of the customer for violation of the term and order of payment of goods (works, services) during procurement to provide state and municipal needs" will be able to improve the payment discipline of public customers.
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia on the initiative of the Prosecutor General.
The new law will be supplemented by an article of the Code of the Russian Federation on administrative offences, which provides for a fine of 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation of the term and order of payment of goods, works and services by a public and municipal purchases by an official of the customer.
If the official has already been subject to administrative punishment for a similar offence, he will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the Russian Federation's subjects have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative novelties in practice.
Civil rights group announces a travel warning in Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning for people of color traveling to Missouri because of the state's discriminatory policies and racial slurs.
