People are being violated in your country.
They're stopped on the roads because of their skin color, beaten and killed, said Rod Chapel, president of the Missouri National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, to the Kansas City Gazette.
We hear complaints more often than ever before.
This is the first such warning the organization has issued to the U.S.
The group referred to incidents such as the humiliation of black students on the grounds of race at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under suspicious circumstances earlier this year after running out of gas while on a state tour, and Missouri State Police arrested him without charge.
The warning also mentions a recent report from the Missouri Attorney General's Office that says black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped on the road than white drivers.
"The purpose of the warning is for people to be aware of the situation and to warn their relatives and friends and colleagues about what could happen in Missouri", Chapel said.
People should be prepared to take the money with them or tell their relatives they're traveling across the state.
