When I cook lunch, Bardina DeGea doesn't use a stove.
She's not even a potty.
In her wooden house in Enoratali, the capital of Panay County in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually simply places a sweet potato, called notata, right in the stove.
In half an hour, the burned club is removed and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
DeGee sits on the ground floor, she has no furniture, and it's where she does her housework, like washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The toilet is a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband's four wives, and so she was not assigned to work in the fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men in this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
"Nobody dares to walk around the village after five o'clock", she says.
It's a rare opportunity to look at everyday life in the high mountains of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a questionable referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote, publicly raising their hands in front of the occupying forces.
The existing movement for independence from the Netherlands quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which maintains tight control over the region, barring foreign journalists and human rights defenders.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and Western Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enoratali is as remote as it is abandoned; the road to this city includes a one-and-a-half-hour flight from Jaipur, the administrative centre of the province, to Nabir, and then a five-hour drive by rental car.
There's no public transportation here.
The town of about 19,000 people is made up of wooden houses with bamboo fences; the roofs of the town are made of corrugated steel and are painted with rust in various reddish shades.
Few Indonesians, let alone journalists, and almost no foreigners have been here.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Papuans worshiped a god named Ug Tamie.
There were other changes.
"We were not used to wearing these clothes", DeGea says, pointing to his bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt, and bright shirt.
Previously on the body we only carried leaves.
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's golden land.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by the Phoenix-based company Freeport McMoran, is located just sixty miles from Panay, a mountainous province about the size of New Jersey, home to 153,000 people.
