The coroner covers the body of one of the victims of the Morse Ford lynching on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI records obtained by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and surrounding counties were suspected of being involved in the lynching.
But no one has ever been charged.
Although the suspects have been on the loose for decades, human rights defenders say they have always been well aware of the two linked motives of lynchings in the city: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court decision allowed black citizens to vote for the first time in the primaries that summer.
About the same time, the FBI reports that a black usher, Roger Malcolm, stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, in a fight, apparently because of a woman.
Brooks says that rumours spread around the city that Hester slept with Malcolm's wife Dorothy and that the child she was due to have was not from her husband.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Louis Harrison, a large white landowner, paid $600 bail to free Malcolm from prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they drove out of prison and into the Morse Ford Bridge, a crowd of lynchmen surrounded the car.
"It turns out that Harrison organized and commanded the murders", says one of the FBI reports.
"It's also clear that there was a conspiracy between state and city law enforcement who not only participated in the murders, but also destroyed the evidence and concealed the identities of the witnesses".
Brooks calls it shorter.
"It was an attempt on voting rights", he says.
"They were all killed to send a signal to the black people in the city that if you register and vote, you will be the same".
For almost a decade, Cassandra Green has directed an annual performance that recreates the lynching at the Morse Ford Bridge.
Her play is eye-catching, it captivates the audience and it tells the story of the deep racism that many would like to believe is no longer present in America.
It's hard to look at and even harder to turn away, but Green thinks that's the point.
"We don't want to talk about Lynch's courts because they show us our own ugliness", she says.
"But I can't build a relationship with you unless you hear me or hear what I've been through".
This year's rehearsal began in June, and on the first day, nearly 30 actors - a dozen white, the rest black - gathered in the room to listen to the play's years-long review.
Wade Marbo was the director with Green.
He's been the chief of the clan for years, but he says the role has never been easier.
"I feel like I'm screwed up because I'm not the person I am", Marbo says.
"But I think it's very important to remember that story because we don't want to go back to that time".
Inside, actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascon, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, are reprising their roles.
The show begins with Malcolm, angry that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, screaming and pushing him.
"I said, nigga, get out of my house!"
Raconka is yelling in response.
It's a blow.
And at the same time, everyone (at least all the black actors) is upset.
Green laughs louder than anyone.
"What is it?" Asks Askona.
He's worried and embarrassed.
Am I winning?
"No", says Green with a laugh.
"I just don't think white people used to say 'nigga' back then".
"Yeah, yeah", laughs one of the black performers.
"You have to put the hard 'p' in it".
And so the energy in the room changes: discomfort is replaced by a sense of companionship.
Everyone should do everything right, not only for the play, but for the memory of the four people killed.
The scene starts again.
This time, when Rasconka says the word for the letter "n", it gets clear and sharp.
No one laughs.
The show ends violently and quickly.
Screams, shots, and then silence.
A woman in mournful black dress stands over the bodies of actors and sings Billy Holiday's sad song "Strange Fruit".
Her voice is interrupted by a word.
A hundred yards away, half a hundred spectators are wiped out with tears and sweat.
There's almost the same number of black and white people in the audience.
A couple came from Ithaca, New York, to see the show; many live nearby.
They all endured Georgia's harsh wind for almost eight hours while Brooks took them on a pilgrimage to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Up until that point, the murders were history, but now that they're standing in the same place where they lynched people, it seems like their ghosts are hanging in the air.
When the last note of the song is silenced, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
The children bend over their heads, touch the paint that shows blood and still bodies and whisper something to each other.
"They're not really dead", murmurs one little boy, as if to remind himself.
In a few minutes, Green thanks the audience, and then it's over.
Actors drop the rope off their necks and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbo, the man in the suit who played the main puppet sklan.
Nick Rasconka hugs two other actors and suddenly, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional burden of the play finally falls on him.
"It's all right", one of the women whispered.
"We know your heart is good.
You had a reason for it".
Later, the audience sits down to dinner with the actors.
At one table, a white couple from Atlanta is excitedly discussing a performance with a black couple they just met.
Denise Daplinsky has a hard time finding words to describe how she feels after the performance.
"It was hard to listen to those horrible, horrible words and actions... of people who look like you and who do it because they look like you", she says.
"After that, I think lynchings are still happening", she adds, "but now it's called shooting by the police".
The other corner of the room was dominated by Tyrone Brooks, who recalls his work as a human rights defender at dinner.
He says he's already started planning his next year's performance.
"The play is inspiring because it not only describes the horror of what we have been through but also teaches us", he says.
"Because if you don't learn from this, it could happen again.
Those who do not study their history, who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it".
