How football's financial rules will affect Neymar's move to Paris
The rules aimed at preventing unlimited spending by European football clubs do not prevent the world record-setting Neymar from transferring from Spanish Barcelona to French Paris Saint-Germain.
Whatever the consequences may be, it's up to Paris Saint-Germain to be held by UEFA, the governing body that controls European football, and whose authority is to ban teams from the prestigious Champions League.
From the rules of the financial fair play introduced by UEFA in 2011, it follows that the PSJ will eventually have to show that Neymar's transfer was financed without major losses.
Barcelona paid 222 million euros ($262 million) just to free the Brazilian from his contract, and Neymar will get a salary that will reach tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some of the financial aspects of Neymar's move to France.
The PSJ can certainly lavish itself to hire Neymar and add him to the galaxy of other stars, given the team's funding from the powerful ruling family of Qatar.
Clubs have the right to spend large sums of money on players, but they have to balance them with legitimate sources of income to reach the threshold of profitability in their football business.
The FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA president in 2007.
The former French footballer believed that clubs that incur huge debts in their quest for success were in fact cheating and risking bankruptcy if banks or owners stopped financing.
In 2011, the FFP stopped focusing on clubs' debts and instead switched to tracking their losses.
As a result of this change, the business model that Roman Abramovich initially used in Chelsea in 2003 to buy a club with good potential, and then spend heavily to improve the team and create a global brand, became a difficult plan.
During the current three-year assessment period, which spans 2018, clubs could suffer losses of 30 million euros.
And despite Platini being disgraced by his removal from the presidency in 2015, his successor at UEFA, Alexander Cheferin, is still determined to curb excessive spending.
Of course, FFP is alive, and we're moving forward, we're going to tighten the rules, Andrea Traversó, who controls FFP at UEFA, told the Associated Press last week.
Although the PPSJ will pay Neymar's contract at the same time, he can distribute the sum for the duration of his contract.
Neymar signed a five-year contract, so the transfer fee can be shown in the annual report as a cost of 44.4 million euros over the next five years.
During the first wave of sanctions in 2014, severe sanctions were imposed on the PPSJ, as well as the Abu Dhabi-owned Manchester City.
PSJ was fined 60 million euros (at that rate it is 82 million dollars), which was later reduced to 20 million euros, and was ordered to limit its squad in the Liga dei Campioni during the 2014-1015 season to 21 players instead of the usual 25.
UEFA tracks clubs that may try to trick its financial inspections by inflating their income at the expense of companies associated with the club's owners.
Although a Qatari company could sponsor the PPSJ, if the amount of funding were to exceed the standard market prices, UEFA would not allow it to be considered a legitimate income.
This is exactly what happened in 2014 when UEFA decided that the amount of funding for the Qatar Tourism Authority was inflated.
It was reported that part of Neymar's salary in PSJ could have come in the form of payments from the 2022 World Cup organizing committee in Qatar.
But the PJSC and Qatar 2022 deny Neymar will be the ambassador for the World Cup, and a similar maneuver could easily be detected by UEFA inspectors.
The past sanctions imposed on the PJSC mean that UEFA will be more vigilant about any attempts to circumvent the rules.
As people familiar with the situation reported on Thursday, UEFA has not held any preliminary discussions with the PSJ about Neymar's transfer.
They spoke to the Associated Press on condition of anonymity, as they are not authorized to discuss the situation.
According to the latest published report, in 2015-1016, ПСЖ received more than 10 million euros in profit with a turnover of 542,4 million euros.
The last financial year's report has not yet been published.
The PJS expects Neymar's arrival to be a good base for sponsorship deals, sales of attributes and team logo shirts.
The club expects to increase turnover by at least 30 percent due to hiring a new player.
Undoubtedly angry that one of the best footballers was leaving, the Spanish league tried to prevent Neymar's transfer, saying that PSJ would violate the financial fair play.
"This is an obvious case of financial doping, with the club and the state", La Liga president Javier Tebas told the Spanish newspaper AS, noting that Qatar is the ultimate owner of the PPSJ.
Arsenal coach Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by the American sports mogul, shares La Liga's doubts about the club's state funding.
"It's all the consequences of participation, and it's completely changed the landscape of football over the last 15 years", Wenger said on Thursday.
When the club belongs to the country, anything is possible.
It's getting very difficult to keep up with financial fair play because a country can have many ways and many reasons to be represented by such a serious player.
The President will determine the order and place of the oath .
Where and how new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the president - such amendments to the second reading of the relevant law have been developed by the State Duma's Committee on Legislation and State Construction.
A week ago, the deputies were planning to put the oath of office into law.
Children under 18 years of age and those with disabilities will be exempted from taking the oath of office, according to the revised text of the amendments to the draft law "On citizenship of the Russian Federation" (available to Izvestia), which the committee will consider before its second reading on July 11.
The idea of taking the oath of office when becoming a Russian citizen instead of signing documents was supported by President Vladimir Putin on June 6 during a meeting with State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
The deputies formulated this idea as an amendment to the second reading of a bill that would repeal the decision to grant citizenship to those convicted of a number of terrorist or extremist crimes: for example, public appeals to terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the internet (Article 2 of Article 205.2 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation), as well as the theft of an aircraft, train or water transport, but only if the act is connected with terrorism (Article 4 of Article 211 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation).
According to the bill, the logic was this: when you file your citizenship documents, you sign a promise to abide by Russian law - you're on the path of extremism, and you're breaking that promise.
The bill was introduced in April by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasiliev ("United Russia"), Gennady Zyuganov (KPRF), Vladimir Zirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov ("Justice Russia") and the Speaker of the State Duma, Вячеслав Volodin.
On May 19, the deputies adopted it in first reading.
Last week, the Department of State's Committee on Civil Engineering and Legislation approved the text of the bill for second reading, but now it has been revised once again.
Now it says the order of taking the oath will be established by the president of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, the parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "On citizenship of the Russian Federation", indicating that the ceremony should be held in a solemn setting in front of the state coat of arms and the flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, the text of the bill did not explain where such an event should take place - the list of places where the Russian Federation's coat of arms may be placed, regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, the cabinets of the heads of state authorities of the subjects, municipal bodies, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive authorities, etc.
It's most likely the Zags.
Those wishing to obtain Russian citizenship will take the oath of office after the officials check their documents.
But a Russian passport is only available after taking an oath, according to the revised text.
A week ago, the draft said that the oath must be taken before the decree is signed.
The updated text says that Russia will be sworn in at 18 years old, not 14.
The rule is that those who are incapable or limited in their ability to take an oath or who cannot pronounce, read or sign the oath will be exempt from taking the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt "other persons" from this procedure,
The new draft law also stipulates a special procedure for admitting Ukrainian residents who are considered Russian speakers to Russian citizens.
They will have to officially renounce their Ukrainian citizenship, submitting a corresponding application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the statement will need to be sent to Russian officials.
The right to refuse "foreign" citizenship, as it is now, will not be required if it is provided for in an international treaty or if it is not possible "for reasons other than personal".
The corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, among whom the first deputy speaker of the GD, Ivan Melnikov (KPRF), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Kрашенинnikov and Ayrat Farrachov (all - "United Russia").
I think many of you know that getting a visa from Ukraine is unrealistic, it's just impossible.
Accordingly, many people are waiting for their fate to be decided on the issue of Russian citizenship, - explained the head of the Duma committee on state building and legislation Pavel Kрашенинnikov (ER).
In addition, the text clarified that restrictions on certain positions for foreigners will not apply to those who have written off their "other" citizenship and submitted their previous passport to the Russian Interior Ministry, but "for reasons not related to it" they have not ceased to be considered citizens of another country.
Now foreigners are prohibited from holding positions in the municipal service, being accepted for work at facilities and organizations whose activities are related to the security of Russia.
A person with dual citizenship or residence permit from another country cannot become a deputy of the State Duma or a member of the Federation Council.
The law is scheduled to enter into force on September 1, 2017, and the necessary sub-law acts must be ready by that time.
Nostalgia is getting a little bit nicer in Hot American Summer and Detective's Companion.
The current iteration of the story is nostalgic for the characters' glory days in the '80s; the grunge era in the '90s (about the time when the great masters David Wayne and Michael Showalter made the sketch comedy "The State" for MTV); and for themselves - that is, 2001 before her stars like Elizabeth Banks, Amy Poller and Paul Rudd moved on to bigger things.
As a cultural fact, it's both the height and the embodiment of our era with its constant Facebook reminders.
But as a franchise, it seems anachronistic.
"The First Day of Camp" was surprisingly good, and not only because of the absurdist humor (including the original story of the talking vegetable bank that H. John Benjamin voiced).
The result is a double-header of the main joke: middle-aged actors play sexually disturbed children who have just reached adulthood; thus, the impossibility of returning to the stage becomes part of the joke.
"Ten Years Later", where adults played adults, has less deep emotional roots and its parody is more systematic and includes riffs from the '90s stalker films like "Hands That Lift the Crib".
In one episode, the character gets an Apple Powerbook, four-wheel roller skis, and "a bunch of other stuff from 1991".
Many of the storylines are the same.
Goodwill Cooper (Showalter), now a writer, has yet to get a return from Katie (Margarith Morrow).
Victor (Ken Marino) has not yet broken his virginity.
And there's a crazy, mean conspiracy involving Ronald Reagan (also Showalter), now being incited by George W. Bush (a tried-and-true parody of Michael Ian Blake).
As always, the best part of a franchise is stepping back.
It's especially fun to see a forever young Rad singing Matt Dillon's song from "Lonely", whose character, former big man Andy, now looks old.
The success of this franchise could be a random madness in the spirit of the recurring series Seven Up until it reaches what I think would be its logical conclusion: "Hot American Summer: Twenty Years Later", where the entire company would go to the movies for the premiere of "Hot American Summer".
"The Detective Comrade" in the Amazon is a different kind of nostalgia: Cold War memories from "The Americans", "Blurb blonde" or even "Blink" with her images of the struggle of East and West.
This comedy, created by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka with director Riz Thomas, is a television film: a 1980s Romanian police drama about two policemen in Bucharest fighting for truth, atheism and the Marxist-Leninist path.
The main roles - the life-threatening Gregor and the idealist Joseph - are played by Florin Piersic Jr. and Corneliu Ulich, and voiced by their dialogue in English by Chenning Tatum (the same executive producer) and Joseph Gordon-Levitt.
That's a brilliant idea.
But it's just an idea.
There are a few visual jokes (police spend time watching a chess match, like Americans would watch football).
The famous behind-the-scenes voice-over team - including Jenny Slate, Nick Oferman, Mahershala Ali and Chloe Sevigny - makes it interesting to play "Guess Who".
But the Co-Detective is so caught up in the truthfulness of a clumsy propaganda drama - there's even a killer in Ronald Reagan's mask - that it often looks like it.
Six long episodes are long, and it's not funny very often.
If it were shorter, the "Comrade Detective" would have been better able to handle its satire in the spirit of agitproofness; for example, every time Gregor and Joseph come to the American embassy, there are two fat men sitting in the lobby eating a bunch of hamburgers.
To the imaginary communist audience, this image tells us that Western culture can make anything a meal.
The fictional Romanian filmmakers are not so wrong: we do this even with our own recent history, and with theirs.
