Bank of England will keep interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce later that interest rates will remain unchanged after weak economic growth and weak inflation have caused rumors of a possible increase to subside.
The Bank of England warned that economic growth would remain slow and left interest rates unchanged amid rising pressure on household incomes.
The Bank's Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted 6-2 to keep rates at 0.25%, with fewer committee members this month voting to raise rates because weak economic growth has weakened support for the increase.
In its quarterly inflation report, the bank limited its forecasts to a rise of 1.7% in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018 and warned that the pressure on family incomes would continue, while inflation is still expected to rise to about 3% in the fall.
However, the bank warned that interest rate hikes over the next few years would be necessary to control Brexit-induced inflation, and said that borrowing costs would likely have to rise more strongly than expected in financial markets.
The committee also voted to abandon part of the huge economic development package launched a year ago as a result of Brexit.
Starting next February, the bank will close a timely financing plan, which it provides banks with cheap loans, although it has said it will now have to provide another £15 billion to £115 billion under that plan.
In the minutes on the decision on rates, the bank said: According to the main forecasts of the MPC, the growth of gross domestic product (GDP) in the near future will remain slow, while the pressure on real household incomes continues to affect consumption.
On the issue of rates, he reiterated that to halt inflation, it would require some tightening of financial policy, somewhat more than the markets expect.
At the moment, the markets are predicting their first increase in the third quarter of next year and another  in 2020.
But the bank stressed that all increases would be gradual and limited.
The bank's forecast for this year and next is lower than the forecasts it made in May, which were 1.9% and 1.7%.
The bank has kept its forecast unchanged at 1.8% in 2018.
After this news, the sterling fell against the dollar and the euro.
The pound fell 0.5% to 1.31 US dollars and 0.4% to 1.11 euros.
The decision not to change the rate was made after recent discouraging growth rates weakened the increased expectation of a rise; GDP then grew by 0.3% in the second quarter against 0.2% in the previous three months.
According to the bank's spokesman, growth is expected to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it will start to increase slightly at the end of the year.
The bank's latest inflation report gave little reason for rejoicing to households hit by high inflation and very slight wage increases: the bank said the pressure would increase before it decreased.
The bank added that financial policy could not prevent a pay shortage in the next few years, but expects wages to recover significantly by the end of its three-year forecast.
The economy is also set to grow as a result of rising demand for British goods, driven by the low pound rate, which offsets part of the lower consumer spending.
The decision came a year after the rate was cut to 0.25% last August after the shocking results of the referendum on leaving the European Union led to a drop in the pound.
The bank estimates that it will likely take four years to fully influence prices and the economy.
Before the bank made its final decision on rates, there was a growing buzz around the proposed rate hike, as inflation increasingly pressured the already strong households: three committee members asked for a rate hike to 0.5% in July.
Last month inflation fell to 2.6 percent from 2.9 percent in July, although the bank said the fall was expected and will be offset again in the coming months.
According to the bank, the higher rate than the planned 2% is entirely a consequence of the low pound.
Andrew Montlake, CEO of Coreco Mortgage Brokers, said: "If you consider the recent drop in swap rates, it looks like the mortgage market will become even more competitive again, as lenders demand business opportunities and expect a good year to end.
The market seems particularly favourable for those who are nearing the end of their existing contracts, as refinancing loans, often with no commission and low interest rates, is becoming more popular than ever.
State health service will prescribe a controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
Starting in September, patients will be able to access the revolutionary HIV prevention drug after a battle in the High Court over funding from the State Health Service.
The National Health Service announced that pre-exposure HIV prevention (PREP), a pill taken before sex that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in those at risk by an average of 86 percent, will now be provided by the health service to about 10,000 people during the initial three-year trial period.
She agreed to fund the trial after the appeals court upheld a High Court ruling last year that the National Health Service had the option to pay for the PREP despite her claims that it should be funded by local authorities.
The move, announced Thursday, was hailed as a "most important innovation" by the president of England's National Health Service, Simon Stevens, and the National AIDS Control Agency (NAT) called it a "turning point".
Before the programme is fully launched across England by April 2018, the venereology clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to register people, and more will join the programme in October.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PREP)  is a course of HIV medications taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PREP significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection among people at risk.
PrEP is given to a person before sex, and they take enough of certain medications to prevent HIV infection.
You can take these medications daily or no later than two hours before sex.
Patients eligible for the drug include gay and bisexual men, transgender people, and people whose partners are HIV positive and are not receiving successful treatment.
Dispensers will select suitable participants who have agreed to participate in the study, including men, women, transgender people and individuals whose partners are unknown whether their HIV status is being curbed by antiretroviral therapy.
People living and registered with a GP in England will also be able to apply for potential participation in the nearest venereal clinic participating in the programme.
The programme will cost £10 million, and the NHS has signed a contract for the drug this week after an international tender.
The study is designed to assess the potential of PREP by collecting clinical data on who the drug is targeted to, its absorbability and wide-ranging use.
This important innovation should complement and strengthen the wider and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
This is another milestone in over three decades of success in combating one of the greatest health threats facing humanity.
Deborah Gold, president of NAT, said: "This is a turning point in the fight against HIV.
The PEP, if properly targeted at people who are in need and at risk, will make a difference to the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, people at risk for HIV, thanks to this study, which is being conducted in England by the National Health Service, will have access to a new, open-ended tool that people can control using themselves without discussing it with their partners, which will improve many, many lives.
We welcome this news.
Ian Green, president of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: "Now the first thing we need to do is make sure that the test is spread across the country quickly and that no one in the HIV risk group is forgotten.
Now that we've got the experimental PREP, we're moving on to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk for HIV.
Shadow Public Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: "We welcome the start of the PREP trial, which has been delayed by months of delays and government wires.
The data shows how revolutionary this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and stopping the transmission of this fatal infection.
This test will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PREP.
Now it's important that the test is rolled out nationwide as soon as possible to protect those at risk for HIV and to take us one step further to stop the spread of HIV in society.
