Judges are offering to protect from presidents
The Presidential Council on Human Rights (CHR) on the instructions of Vladimir Putin has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judicial branch of the government.
The JCC proposes to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts and to introduce their electiveness.
For the courts of appeals and cassation, the SPH wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court must also make its proposals under the presidential mandate.
The IPC has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of the Russian judiciary.
The task was carried out by the President of the Russian Federation on 3 January 2017 on the instructions of Vladimir Putin, who gave the task after meeting with the members of the Council.
The meeting with the members of the council on 8 December 2016 discussed, among other things, individual cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as the problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see "Ъ" of 9 December).
The work of the JCPU resulted in 25 proposals, which concern both the independence of judges and the identification of judicial errors, and the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin's human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts to increase the independence of the other judges.
If the candidate for the position of judge has successfully passed the competition and has received the support of the judges' community, the chairman of the court, according to the SPI, must submit him to the appointment, without having the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed to deprive the chairman of the right to distribute cases for consideration between judges.
Experts believe that a specially written computer program can do this.
The SPC also considers that the chairman is not entitled to "predetermine the results of the qualification of the judge, initiate his involvement in disciplinary responsibility, decide on the establishment of additional material payments".
The President's Council also considered it necessary to "elect the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves" and "assign them with powers for a relatively short period with mandatory rotation".
Now all the presidents of the courts (from the republican to the district) are appointed for six years by the president on the proposal of the chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
To protect judges from pressure from regional authorities, the SCHP proposes to reorganize appeals and cassation in courts of common jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The SPH says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation instances not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts".
Experts are based on the practice of arbitration courts.
They have "court districts" that do not correspond to the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee greater independence from regional officials, who have difficulty using the "telephone right".
The ICC proposes that the judges of the world be strengthened by the people's councils to consider with their participation certain "categories of civil and administrative cases".
For example, deprivation of parental rights, restoration at work, protection of honor and dignity, deprivation of driver's rights, etc.
"It's just our proposals", explained the SPC member, retired Constitutional Court judge Tamara Morshkova.
She also recalled that the President's order was not only for the SPH, but also for the Supreme Court (Supreme Court), which has not yet revealed its proposals.
The Air Force (among its co-executors - the Prosecutor General's Office and the Russian Human Rights Commissioner) still has time to fulfill the task.
Vladimir Putin should be informed by the Chairman of the Russian Armed Forces, Vyacheslav Lebedev, of how effectively the independence of the judiciary is being ensured in Russia.
Living a high life: a half-floor and clever design techniques have turned this little apartment into an Earl's Court apartment into a spacious dwelling
Joan Lee, a former banker who has a passion for real estate repair, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the first floor of a pretty Queen Anne style typical house, and in favor of the new design, it says that Joan didn't pack her things and moved again.
