Since the first inspection, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has been completely renovated.
It was originally a one-bedroom apartment with a complex layout. To get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen. Joanna wanted to add storage space and a half-floor to maximize the benefits of the generous height of the ceilings.
I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
"That was my requirement", she says.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from Notting Hill's architectural design studio Duck & Shed to use the 12.5-foot ceilings and create a home that would not only be a successful project, but would be suitable for Joan to live in.
The floor was not high enough to fit two rooms on top of each other, so the architectural task was to create a half-floor where you could stand upright.
Erfan had to think creatively to handle the brief.
Working with steel structures is very difficult, he explains.
We had to arrange the rooms so that they were on top of each other, and we didn't have to bend.
It was not just a simple platform that needed to be built, but a curved structure that would be at the right height and allow the space to be used from above and below.
This decision allowed Erfan to set up two full-sized rooms one above the other in a secluded space and much more interesting.
From the half-floor through the copper window from Retrouvius, you can see the luxurious living room below.
Mirror furniture with gold finish, silver accents and vintage lighting fixtures from Serge Muy set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacle, space and light.
The short corridor is framed with mirrors to make it look longer.
In the kitchen, the mirrored panel looks like a window into another room.
The mirror cabinets at the entrance are used to store all of Joan's dishes.
To create a more luxurious sense of space, the beauty of the living room can enclose the kitchen when it's not in use.
There's nothing new about the folding kitchens.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it's a door that moves upwards, like a garage.
"Here was the engineering art", Erfan tells of a steel armored wooden-fibre shield door.
It's equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily.
Using space and storage space wisely, Joan was given an additional 16 square feet, an additional bedroom, and improved planning.
"After all, the floor area is what you're going to sell, that is, what your property is valued at", says Erfan.
In short, the real estate agent will come in and make the calculations based on the floor area.
Here they were able to increase the floor area using high-quality materials that give the space a shade of luxury.
Materials  are what we touch, so they help to create an emotional connection with the home", says Erfan.
Nobody loves a wire in the walls.
It's important, but it doesn't touch our hearts.
This is proof that with a good design and an increased meterage, an apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you may decide to stay.
