"In Libya, we do not want to be associated with any side of the conflict"
The Russian authorities have recently significantly intensified their policies in the Libyan direction, and with visits to Moscow, delegations from the opposing Libyan sides have joined.
The head of the Russian contact group for intra-Libyan settlement under the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma, the assistant to the head of the Chechen Republic Lev Daygov told "Ъ", what goals Moscow is pursuing in this region and who is betting on.
There's almost no information about the contact group you're leading in Libya.
Let's say the contact group in Ukraine is known.
And here's the curtain of secrecy.
What exactly do you do, what are your goals?
The contact group was created on the initiative of the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma.
Its activities are supervised by the Deputy Foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimhanov (Duma deputy from Chechnya. - "Ъ").
The last one is authorized to work in Libya by State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
The group was formed in response to the detention of a Russian tanker "Mehanik Chebotarev" in Libya (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board).
We've been thinking about how to help the crew.
At that time, a contact group of military experts, representatives of the State Duma, was established, and our work was supported by the head of Chechnya, Ramzan Kadyrov.
How come you're the one who led it?
Since I've been working in Libya since 2008, I've been asked to lead the group.
Our activities were not limited to the release of the seamen from the Mechanic Chebotarev.
We have been able to establish contacts with representatives of all the major groups facing each other in the Libyan conflict - both from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government headed by Faiz Sarraj is based) and Tobruk (the residence of the parliament that opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern regions of Libya.
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Vice Prime Minister of Libya - "Ъ"), we were able to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
And that's when it was decided to make more effective use of those contacts, to create a contact group.
Her task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, dialogue with all sides of the conflict.
I want to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to be associated with any side of the conflict, we are engaged in dialogue with all sides.
How many people are in the contact group and how many are in Libya on a regular basis?
There are five people in the contact group now.
Among them are people with experience in the military, including the Ministry of Defence.
We also want to include a group of experts from the region, representatives of the Institute for the Middle East of the Russian Federation.
There are no staff in Libya at all, so there's no need for that.
Are there any Russian military advisers or instructors in Libya now?
And if so, whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All the talk and the publicity about it is not true.
But your contact group includes former military personnel...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
Like when we visit hot spots.
Or cities that have been closed to us for a while, like Misurata (where militia units are based, which played a role in the overthrow of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and have become increasingly active in the years since.
We arrived in Misurata in January of this year.
We were scared, they said that they were all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why these rumors are going around, what the role of Islamists is really.
In Misrata, we met with all the representatives of the detachments that were destroying ISIS in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was captured by the militants of the banned "Islamic State" - "Ъ" in Russia).
We wanted to look at them, meet these people, see if they were the ones who played a crucial role in destroying ISIS in Libya, not the caliph Haftar who claimed that credit.
So what's your conclusion?
Is it not Haftar who defeated the Islamic State in Libya?
He didn't do that.
Haftar was operating on the other front, in Benghazi.
And ISIS in Sirte was fought by government-owned structures in Tripoli.
And, by the way, we invited people to Russia who were conducting this counterterrorism operation.
And they came - the visit lasted from April 19 to 23, this year, and the Libyan delegation was welcomed into the Federation Council, the State Duma, the Foreign Ministry and the Rosgwardi.
You've been to every region in Libya, and you're probably imagining the mood of the local elites and field commanders.
Do you think the ceasefire agreement reached in late July in Paris by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Sarag will be implemented?
Or again, as has happened many times in the past, will agreements be broken, will hostilities resume, will the parties try to seize power alone?
The fact that Saradj and Haftar agreed to meet again was a good sign for us.
In the recent past, both leaders have received extremely negative reviews about each other.
As for Russia's position...
There are many reports that Moscow actively supports Haftar, and many believe this.
We faced this situation when we were in Misrata, and it was on this very day that Haftar was boarding the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov.
It was a coincidence.
But in Misrata, they didn't believe in coincidence.
They said, "You must be very brave people to come to us today".
But our task is to show that we are not only supporting Haftar, we are engaging in dialogue with all the key players in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar were talking.
Does the fact that he studied in the USSR twice make it easier to understand Russian partners on a human, emotional level?
And by the way, does Haftar speak Russian?
If he knows Russian, he's very relative.
But what he learned from us, of course, makes it easier to have a conversation with him.
And not just with him, by the way.
When we talk to the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who have studied in Russia or the Soviet Union.
And they speak Russian very well.
And they're drawn to Russia, and they're somewhat nostalgic for it.
Do you think it's possible to lift the arms embargo against Libya soon?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in Russian arms supplies?
They are interested, of course, but as I said, we are not taking sides in this conflict and we would not like to arm some to the detriment of others.
We'd like everyone to be in roughly equal positions.
As for the arms embargo, there are constant calls from the Libyans for Russia to help lift it.
The process of drafting a constitution is now underway in Libya.
We hope that the parties will reach a compromise, reach an internal consensus.
Then there's an election, which was discussed at the meeting between Saraj and Haftar.
If elections are held and a legitimate government is finally elected (and now none of the parties have such a status), then the UN Security Council can raise the issue of lifting the arms embargo.
Raising this question now is pointless and dangerous, it will only escalate the conflict.
Recently, the media reported that Italy, facing the problem of African refugees arriving from Libya, feels left behind by its EU allies.
Can Moscow help Italian partners in this situation by using its links with the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is the possibility that Haftar's squads will establish control of the coast and put an end to the smuggling of immigrants to Europe?
It's a very timely question.
We're working hard on that.
The Italians need Russia's support because Moscow is engaged in dialogue with Haftar, Saraj, Misurata and the south of the country.
And the tribes in southern Libya are very important in this, and they are willing to cooperate with Russia.
Is this about the southerners stopping the flow of migrants on long-distance approaches?
So, you mean, conditionally, rolling back buses that carry Nigerian migrants?
That's what we're trying to do.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these flows going.
We hope to help unite the southerners in the negotiation process between the Saraj, Haftar and the southern tribes.
But first, we'd like to see a consensus on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
The head of government in Tripoli, Faiz Saradj, is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction of Sharia law in the country.
How radical is his view?
Will this not be an obstacle to building relations with Russia or the West?
I'll give my personal opinion about him.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But there are Islamists in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself holds the position that Libya should be an absolutely normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
And he's also actively fighting terrorists.
How did he get that reputation?
It's created by countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, and there is the legislative, executive and judicial branches.
There's a national oil corporation, a national bank and other government agencies.
Of course, some countries were interested in keeping us out of it.
We've been mixing up all the cards and we've been actively communicating with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we're already reaping the rewards of this: Rosneft has signed a cooperation agreement with Libya's state-owned oil company, NOC.
Director of NOC Mustafa Sanalla, with whom Rosneft head Igor Sechin had a deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil from Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with it?
I guess I'll have to sell it.
What other economic interests does Russia have in Libya?
Plans to re-sign contracts signed under Muammar Gaddafi.
In particular, the agreement on transport (railway construction), energy (electricity) and other matters has been reached.
And the Libyans have anything to pay for?
Well, they have oil.
So, like Iran, is this a "oil for services" scheme?
I don't know what the scheme is, but I'm not directly involved in these issues.
The economy is not really important to Russia in Libya.
We're actually doing peacekeeping work there.
The key for us is to stop the bloodshed, help the Libyans to reconcile so that they can establish order and Libya is no longer a conducive environment for terrorism.
For Russia, that's the main task of helping the Libyan people and driving out terrorists.
Do you have any evidence of the presence in Libya (now or before) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that no Russian or other ex-USSR nationals are there today.
He said he had about 50,000 phone records of Islamic and radical groups (in Libya) and Russian language was not spoken there.
So what countries are these fighters from?
I don't want to go into that detail.
Then let's put it another way.
How many of the Islamist militants in Libya are Libyans themselves?
There are almost no Libyans among them, no more than 5%.
The rest are just a bunch of things.
Can Moscow conduct intra-Libyan negotiations on the example of Paris?
There are plans.
We are in active negotiations with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow and have declared their readiness to come again - to Moscow or to Grozny.
When can we have these talks?
It's hard to say right now.
There are still a few more visits to make, and I hope that we can be clear about the time and place of the talks.
