Michelle Carter's sentence for the messages that led to Conrad Roy's suicide
A Massachusetts resident was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for encouraging her boyfriend Conrad Roy to commit suicide by texting and making phone calls.
Michelle Carter, now 20, will serve 15 months of her sentence and another five years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the involuntary murder of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father said at a hearing Thursday: "My family is devastated.
My son was my best friend".
Carter was allowed to remain at large until appeal.
She faced a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said she and Roy both suffered from mental illness.
Carter, wearing red pants and a cream blouse, was listening to the verdict standing, shaking hands and lowering her eyes.
"She killed Conrad Roy with her actions", the prosecutor told the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve her own.
She didn't accept responsibility", she said.
"She showed no remorse".
But Carter's lawyer said it was "a tragic case she deeply regrets".
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said that he felt that her "age, maturity, or even mental illness had no significant effect on her actions".
Prosecutor Roy's mother, Lynn Roy, read a statement that said: "Not a day has passed since I mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I'm doing - I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will stay with us forever", it says.
Sister Roya Camden Roy said that she was constantly haunted by the thought of never being able to attend his wedding or become his children's aunt.
"Loss of someone who has been with me since I was born is a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life", she said.
This case is likely to set a legal precedent, since there is no law in Massachusetts that would require a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in his car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case caught the attention of the entire country when it became known that he was motivated to commit suicide by Carter's message.
"You can hang yourself, jump off a roof, stab yourself, I don't know there are many ways", she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death while he was on vacation with his family.
A few minutes before she committed suicide, she wrote, "You have to do this, Conrad" and "You just have to turn on the lighter and you'll be free and happy".
Judge Monis said Carter wanted to get attention with Roy's death, and forbade her to talk to the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
Lawyers have been divided on this matter.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of murdering her British roommate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
Knox, 30, published her opinion in the Los Angeles Times, stating: "Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison".
