By using a computer program to analyze Manning's DNA and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of people who might have had a genome like this, Dewey-Harborg created a profound, though difficult to grasp, manifesto that focused not only on the plasticity of DNA data - the different ways they are interpreted and the inherent determinism of those interpretations - but also the concept of identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has openly identified as a woman since she was a teenager, was convicted in 2013 of 20 counts, including six counts of espionage, computer fraud and theft.
Her photos in prison were unavailable, so only one photo of her was known: a grainy black and white selfie of Manning in a platinum wig, apparently uncomfortable, sitting behind the wheel of a car; this photo was associated with her.
