There's a new kind of startup in the human resources field that helps companies figure out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software that measures employee engagement, they allow companies to do express surveys, contact specific teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and in some cases, allow informants to skip top management and contact directors.
"Now we have health monitoring tools like Strava and Fitbit, and where is Fitbit for your company?" says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Redwood City-based startup Glint, whose analytics programs are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she had gained a better understanding of what her employees think and feel in three years of using Glint.
In addition to express surveys and surveys by certain teams, the product offers a company heat map and shows visually which units have the most complaints and which managers have the lowest approval ratings, allowing it to understand why.
Companies are slowly realizing that they need to control the workplace, or they will become another Uber who was involved in the scandal when a former employee posted a blog post describing an aggressive situation in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For startups like Glint, it's a desire to control the situation - an opportunity for profitable business.
According to the online portal Let's talk about payments, the financial technology, global governance, regulation and compliance industry could be worth over $118.7 billion by 2020.
Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid Uber's declining reputation.
