Recently, Uber has been a client.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customized staff opinion polls, collect confidential answers in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top manager gets hurt, the complaints go straight to the board.
"The court of public opinion has seized power from the inspectors", said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company is not treating employees well or behaving unethically, even if the inspectors do not intervene, the company could face costly consequences such as customer boycotts, employee outflows and lawsuits, Quinnlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with over 25,000 employees in 500 locations, has been using Convercent for over a year to ensure that employees are aware of the rules and procedures and offer an easy way to contact the company's headquarters.
In the past, when an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look up the phone number or email address of the head office, file a formal complaint, and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a scary and awkward experience, said James Vitrano, head of the legal department at Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company uses the Convercent service, problems that were previously hidden from managers in offices in other cities or states  such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay  can be detected and addressed more quickly.
