Creating a comic book: One Castle in English History
In the recent past, the tiny castle of Scotney was featured in the music video "Squeeze", and in the 1970s and 1980s it served as a retreat for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy home in the Bayoule River Valley in Kent County, he's been watching the turbulent history around him, and now he's inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshire man with blond hair and a penchant for historical documents, for comic books.
"I think it's so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago", he says enthusiastically.
"You feel it so personally when you hold this letter in your hand".
The Castle in England covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Evardian era and tells the story of families who lived in Scotland; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkevich, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not the first book by Rhodes to be based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote "Dead Man's Teeth and Other Stories", a collection of British Library documents; this project unexpectedly touched him to the depths of his soul.
"I could have just grabbed a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700's by a double agent working on Jacobites", he says.
"This is his fingerprint".
And the letters always smell like smoke, because back then, they lit a fire to light it.
And 300 years from now, in the future, you'll feel like you're there too.
Oh, I love the archives!"
For a man so passionate about old papers, getting support from the National Trust and the Arts Council of England and living in a castle for four months ("I've been a little bit over there, honestly") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent all day studying the "new" Victorian castle, going through the archives and examining the many treasures of the estate and ancient things - for example, the heads of gynecologists on the walls or bottles lying in the pit for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of an old castle, talking to foresters, gardeners and sometimes artists working on illustrations for his book.
Then at night he "drinked whiskey and sat down to write".
The history of Scotney Castle is not well studied, because the National Trust did not gain full access to it until 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hassie, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff was just beginning to look into the archive, which he describes as "something that the aristocracy had been plunging into the attic for centuries".
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps showing who owned the land: "You think land disputes are boring", says Rhodes, "but this is the place where two families fought over the hedge.
It happens, guys!"
In some stories, the castle becomes a starting point for broader research into English history: for example, in "The Labbotnik", the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
"There is a record of a castle mutiny in 1380 in a book called The Knights of Kent and Sussex", says Rhodes.
"The peasant uprising started in these places, and I thought that the uprising was a good start.
Maybe they were connected?"
Other stories are closely linked to the castle's history, such as "The Priest", which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was kept secret by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "The Smuggler", about the 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by filling the coffin with stones (it was discovered a few years later when the coffin was excavated).
The Darreles were the favourite of the Rhodes family of all Scottish settlers. "The gentlemen seemed to be a complete fraud, constantly in debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darrelas have solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy older women - I imagine they were a company of cute guys who could take care of the heirs of great fortunes".
After completing his work at the Rhodes Castle, he seeks other opportunities to gain unique writing experience.
He spent two weeks in the Finnish hinterland, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elamyanmäki - a place where in the early 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it was again covered with forest.
But Scotney is still a special place for him.
"I felt sad to leave", he says.
"I felt like I had to go back to the real world".
