Red meat, dairy, and chocolate can help ease the symptoms.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies suggest otherwise: A diet rich in protein and dairy products may help ease symptoms in those with inflammatory bowel disease.
This is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, leading to colic and belly swelling, chronic or bloody vomiting, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Usually, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products to alleviate symptoms, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid in the protein tryptophan promotes the production of immune cells that increase gut tolerance.
Leading researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that the immune cells in the gut control the passage of harmful microbes from food into the body.
Cells that are capable of triggering inflammation are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too much distorted toward inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel disease.
Experiments have shown that mice with a certain bacterium in their intestines have increased cell tolerance.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan, one of the building blocks of protein, to start these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is part of the normal gut microbiome - and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more these immune cells they had".
He suggested that the same thing would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could promote a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the gut.
Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barragánvas, a researcher who studied the tolerance-boosting types of immune cells, found that one group of mice had these cells, and another group that was of the same line but was kept separate had none.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the microbiomes of the intestines of mice - communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the mouse gut cells was sequenced, and six types of bacteria were found in mice that had immune cells, but none in mice that didn't.
Mice raised in a sterile environment that didn't have a good microbiome and didn't develop this type of immune cell got L. reuteri, and they had immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then transferred small portions of the fluid - without bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells secreted from mice.
The immune cells have turned into tolerance-boosting cells.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it was a byproduct of tryptophan processing known as indole-3 lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in mice's food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when tryptophan levels were cut in half, the number of cells also doubled.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragán explains that humans have the same elevated cell tolerance as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gut.
It is not known whether the tryptophan by-products of L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans as well as in mice, but defects in the genes associated with tryptophan have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
She says: "We may need to improve the development of these cells, as the inflammatory processes on the intestinal surface depend on them.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri could potentially lead to an expansion of their population".
