The White House receipt cost taxpayers thousands of dollars .
According to the military's records provided to TIME magazine, the White House's decision last month to bring a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as the Marine One when the president is on board, became a central element of the July 17 event at the White House, where American construction programs were demonstrated.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and senior White House officials have reviewed technology products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut-made helicopter was placed next to a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck, and a Mississippi truck.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the department responsible for the helicopter management, the White House Military Administration ordered the helicopter's presence in a private order, or FRAGO, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an unusual event.
"I just wanted to make sure you were aware, because this is an unusual event that's been widely covered in the press", commander HMX-1 wrote in an email to his chief, first deputy chief of naval aviation, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on July 17 for the event, scheduled for 3 p.m., and would remain there until the lawn was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m. that same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the hours of operation restrictions.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel stayed close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records obtained by TIME magazine, it remains unclear whether a second crew was required as a result.
Hatch's law prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 has clarified whether the event is contrary to this order.
"We asked if this was a violation of Hatch's law, among other things, and we were told no", the commander wrote.
"You don't seem to have anywhere else to go", replied the deputy chief.
The event was declared by the White House as an official event, and Hatch's law did not apply to it.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the president made efforts to advance the health care reform that was being worked out in the Senate at the time, and praised the efforts to regulate government regulations.
The use of airships known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are advised to use them for travel.
But asking them for photos is unusual.
Trump was already the subject of discussion in February when the presidential plane flew in the background during his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with complaints about his predecessor using the presidential plane.
"The White House is thrilled with the 'Made in America' show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials", said White House deputy press secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington metropolitan area and the South Lawn to train the transportation of the President of the United States to the White House with an accuracy of one inch.
When Trump was at the G20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 had 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one official, the flight performed for the event was made in America, and the crew was charged for the necessary training flights for a month.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 extra hours that day as part of the non-presidential support tasks.
According to the White House, the taxpayers did not pay for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of the company Sikorsky reported that the company did not participate in organizing a helicopter demonstration on the South lawn.
HMX-1 doesn't keep track of the presidential flights budget, and it's difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Defense Department's 2017 fiscal year hourly rates, the Defense Department's rate of compensation for the VH-3D is $24,380 per hour of flight.
The unit's records record that the aircraft's time in the air was 30 minutes each way from its base at the Quantico Marine Air Base in Virginia.
The White House claims the actual cost of using the helicopter is much lower than that rate.
"It is a mistake to calculate the cost to taxpayers based on the approximate rate of compensation", says Walters.
These exemplary rates include personal allowance, maintenance and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual allowances.
According to a 2015 study by the REND Corporation, the compensation rates do not include the cost of personnel, but actually take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and expenses specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer was speaking out in support of using the helicopter for the event.
The idea is to showcase this week's American-made stuff, Spicer said.
And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they're contributing to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we're all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked so hard to build.
So, of course, it's quite appropriate to pay attention to that.
It was unclear if Trump interacted with the helicopter while patrolling the South Lawn during the event, but he was definitely sitting in the driver's seat in the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed representatives of Sikorsky, joking with the press about his own fleet of company products.
I know Sikorsky very well, the president said.
